<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF110-374-516  </DOCNO><DOCID>10 374 516.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>ACM Transactions on Information Systems  July 1990 v8 n3 p269(20).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Interactive specification of flexible user interface displays.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hudson, Scott e.; Mohamed, Shamim P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>OPUS, the Online Penguims User-interface Specifier, is the userinterface editor of the Penguims UIMS project.andP;  OPUS allows thepresentation component of a Penguims-based user interface to bespecified with little or no programming.andP;  A specific graphicalnotation to specify the presentation component of a user interfaceis used by the OPUS user interface editor.andP;  The four basicnotational constructs are frames, reference lines, constraints,and interactor objects.andP;  These components provide a powerful setof building blocks that can be used to describe a wide range ofuser interface layouts such as a rectangle with a fixed sizepositioned a fixed distance from one corner of its reference frameor a rectangle that stretches to fill the space available to it ora rectangle that stretches to consume a fixed portion of itsowning frame or two rectangles centered below another rectangle.andO;Penguims generated user interfaces can support components thatchange size and position dynamically.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     User InterfaceSoftware EngineeringComputer GraphicsHuman FactorsLanguageInteractive SystemsManipulatorsInterface.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   An interface being created in OPUS. (chart)An open frame. (chart)A composition frame. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>